# Google Cloud Integration Guide for the RBP Web Application

## 1. Purpose

This guide defines how **Google Cloud** should be integrated into the web application to support the platform’s **AI-assisted document operations**, with a specific focus on **Gemini-powered document description, summary, and metadata workflows**.

The current application already includes a lightweight Gemini integration using **Genkit** and the **Google Generative AI plugin**. This guide explains:

- what the application does today
- what the production-ready Google Cloud architecture should look like
- which Google Cloud services are required
- how requests should flow between the web application and Google Cloud
- how security, data handling, logging, and failure recovery should operate
- how the AI workflows should fit into the broader content-management system

This is not just a model hookup guide. It is the operating guide for the whole Google Cloud AI subsystem inside the application.

---

## 2. Scope

This guide focuses on the Google Cloud services and patterns needed to support the application’s AI functionality around document management.

### In scope

- Gemini model access
- Genkit orchestration
- Google Cloud project and API setup
- Vertex AI as the recommended production inference layer
- IAM and service accounts
- Secret management
- file preprocessing and document transport
- logging, monitoring, and auditability
- document generation lifecycle within the app
- interaction with Firebase / Firestore and Cloudflare-hosted application components

### Out of scope

- Google Workspace email setup
- Square billing integration
- full Firebase core setup outside the AI-specific interaction points
- ChatGPT / MCP integration except where it intersects with AI workflow boundaries

