## 5. Recommended Google Cloud Architecture

The recommended architecture depends on whether you want the smallest possible implementation or the most production-safe implementation.

## 5.1 Option A: minimal change architecture

### Pattern

`Next.js server action -> Genkit -> Google AI API key -> Gemini`

### Characteristics

- fastest to implement
- closest to the existing code
- uses `GEMINI_API_KEY`
- suitable for dev or early-stage staging
- weaker enterprise controls

### Use this when

- you need the feature live quickly
- usage volume is low
- document sizes are small
- you are comfortable with an API-key model for the first phase

## 5.2 Option B: recommended production architecture

### Pattern

`Admin UI -> Next.js backend -> AI gateway service on Cloud Run -> Vertex AI Gemini -> Firestore + Cloud Logging + Secret Manager`

### Characteristics

- clean separation between web app and AI execution boundary
- Google Cloud service account authentication
- no direct Gemini API key dependence in the main app runtime
- better IAM, logging, rate control, and operational isolation
- supports future expansion to summaries, metadata, evaluation, and retrieval workflows

### Why this is recommended for your app

Your application appears to be hosted and fronted outside Google Cloud, with Cloudflare handling the infrastructure edge. Because of that, the cleanest production pattern is to keep the primary app where it is, but run the AI boundary inside Google Cloud.

This prevents the main app from becoming a dumping ground for service-account secrets, model logic, and every experimental prompt someone invents after lunch.

