## 10. Authentication and Security Model

This is the most important operational part of the design.

## 10.1 Current authentication model

The current Genkit integration can authenticate with a `GEMINI_API_KEY`.

### Good for

- local development
- prototypes
- limited proof-of-concept deployments

### Weaknesses

- API-key centric
- less granular IAM
- harder to isolate per-environment
- less clean for enterprise production controls

## 10.2 Recommended production authentication model

Use **Vertex AI with Google Cloud service account authentication**.

### Why

- stronger IAM model
- cleaner auditability
- better service isolation
- no need to expose or juggle Gemini API keys in multiple runtimes
- aligns with managed Google Cloud deployment patterns

## 10.3 Recommended trust boundary

| Component | Trust level |
|---|---|
| browser | untrusted |
| admin UI | partially trusted but still client-side |
| app backend | trusted application boundary |
| AI gateway on Cloud Run | trusted AI execution boundary |
| Vertex AI | trusted managed provider |
| Firestore saved result | application source of truth after review |

## 10.4 IAM design

Create dedicated service accounts:

| Service Account | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `rbp-ai-gateway@...` | Cloud Run service identity for Vertex AI calls |
| `rbp-ai-jobs@...` | optional background or queue workers |
| `rbp-observability@...` | optional logging/metrics exporters if separated |

### Minimum IAM roles for AI gateway

| Role | Why |
|---|---|
| Vertex AI User | invoke Gemini models |
| Secret Manager Secret Accessor | read runtime secrets if needed |
| Log Writer | write structured logs |
| Storage Object Viewer | if reading staged files from Cloud Storage |

### Important rule

Use the minimum required roles. Do not give the AI service broad editor or owner access because someone was in a hurry.

