## 11. Secret Management

Secrets should never live in the browser and should not be loosely scattered across different deployment systems.

## 11.1 Secrets likely needed

| Secret | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | only if you keep a fallback API-key path |
| prompt-version tokens or internal config secrets | if used in advanced workflows |
| storage signing keys or related service secrets | only if required by future file flows |

## 11.2 Recommended practice

Store secrets in **Secret Manager** and mount or inject them into the Cloud Run service.

### Why

- central rotation point
- cleaner access control
- environment separation
- safer than pasting secrets into app settings and praying no one screenshots them

## 11.3 App-side recommendation

If the main web app remains on Cloudflare, it should hold as few Google AI secrets as possible.

The preferred model is:

- Cloudflare-hosted app sends an authenticated request to the AI gateway
- AI gateway accesses Vertex AI using its Google Cloud service account
- sensitive Google AI credentials remain inside Google Cloud

