## 17. AI Gateway Design on Cloud Run

If you adopt the recommended production architecture, the AI gateway becomes the main Google Cloud integration boundary.

## 17.1 Role of the gateway

The gateway should:

- accept authenticated requests from the application backend
- validate the AI feature and payload
- invoke Vertex AI Gemini
- enforce model selection and limits
- write structured logs
- return normalized results

## 17.2 What it should not do

The gateway should not:

- publish documents directly
- decide entitlements
- own user role resolution independently of the app
- become a second application backend for unrelated business logic

## 17.3 Recommended endpoints

| Endpoint | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `POST /generate-description` | create a short description |
| `POST /generate-summary` | create summary text |
| `POST /suggest-metadata` | return title, tags, SEO suggestions |
| `GET /health` | runtime health |
| `GET /version` | deployment and prompt version visibility |

## 17.4 Request authentication

Requests from the app to the gateway should be authenticated.

### Recommended choices

- signed service-to-service token
- shared internal secret plus IP/network controls for first phase
- eventually stronger service identity if the app-side hosting model supports it cleanly

